<div id="review_2267416516" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2267416516" />
    <a title="Caleb" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37414448-caleb"><img alt="Caleb" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1625767304p2/37414448.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2267416516?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Caleb" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Caleb" href="/user/show/37414448-caleb">Caleb</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9780441070152" href="/book/show/856031.The_Book_of_Merlyn">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2267416516" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17670483995261607708">&quot;The cheek of the human race,&quot; [Merlyn] exclaimed, &quot;is something to knock you footless. Begin with the unthinkable universe; narrow down to the minute sun inside it; pass to the satellite of the sun which we are pleased to call the Earth; glance at the myriad algae, or whatever the things are called, of the sea, and at the uncountable microbes, going backwards to a minus infinity, which populate ourselves. Drop an eye on those quarter million other species I have mentioned, and upon the unmentio</span>
  <span id="freeText17670483995261607708" style="display:none">"The cheek of the human race," [Merlyn] exclaimed, "is something to knock you footless. Begin with the unthinkable universe; narrow down to the minute sun inside it; pass to the satellite of the sun which we are pleased to call the Earth; glance at the myriad algae, or whatever the things are called, of the sea, and at the uncountable microbes, going backwards to a minus infinity, which populate ourselves. Drop an eye on those quarter million other species I have mentioned, and upon the unmentionable expanses of time through which they have lived. Then look at man, an upstart whose eyes, speaking from the point of view of nature, are scarcely open further than a puppy's There he is, the—the gollywog."</span>
  <a data-text-id="17670483995261607708" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


